{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \D3. With no attractive singleton and a quiet auction, leading low from your three-card holding is a reasonable, safe start.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are South in 4\S. Your spades are a six-card running suit for trump tricks, \DA and \DK give two diamonds, and clubs can be set up for more — you are close, but the tenth trick rides on the diamond guess. The lesson is the two-way finesse for the \DQ: \DAJ6 opposite \DKT8 means finesse East with the jack or West with the ten. Both defenders passed, so build the count from their distribution and the play.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \D3, which conveniently runs right up to your tenace. Treat it as a small holding rather than a help — but note the layout: as you draw trumps and play clubs, watch the discards and lengths. West rates to hold the longer clubs, which would leave East a touch shorter there and with room for diamonds. Where the count is murky, the diamond lead itself slightly favors playing West for not holding the queen behind it. If you are genuinely unsure, this is close to a coin-flip; pick a story, count both hands as the trumps and clubs unwind, and commit. Run an honor and finesse based on whichever defender shows up shorter in diamonds.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] This was a true two-way guess with no bidding to lean on, so you counted the side suits as they ran and let the late shape place the queen. Well done staying patient and gathering count before you committed — that is exactly how you turn a 50/50 into an educated guess.}
