{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \D2, your singleton diamond. A small singleton is a prime lead against a suit contract — you hope partner can win and give you a ruff, and it can't cost a trick from a lone spot card.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 2\H, needing nine for a good result. Trumps give five, and the diamonds give two top tricks plus a third once the \DQ is out, with a long card or two elsewhere — nine if you read the diamond right. You hold \DA\DJ\D3 opposite \DK\DT\D4, missing only the \DQ in a two-way finesse. The opening lead may settle this one for you — watch it closely.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \D2, which looks like a singleton — a low spot with nothing below it, screaming short suit and a hope for a ruff. If West truly began with a singleton diamond, then East holds essentially all the missing diamond length, and the \DQ is almost certainly in East's hand. That is the cleanest possible two-way read: the short hand can't hold the queen you're missing. Rise carefully, draw trumps to kill the ruff, then lead a low diamond from dummy toward your \DA\DJ and finesse the jack into East. It is an inference from the lead, so stay alert, but it is a strong one.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] West's singleton diamond lead handed you the count: with West short, East had the length and therefore the queen, so the jack finesse was a near-certainty rather than a guess. A short-suit lead by one defender is the friendliest clue a two-way finesse can get. Nine tricks, beautifully read off the opening salvo.}
