{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \S3, your singleton spade. Against a suit contract a small singleton is an excellent lead — partner overcalled spades, and you may be able to win a trick elsewhere and score a spade ruff.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 3\H, needing nine. Trumps are worth five, dummy's long spades and your clubs add tricks with ruffs, and the diamonds give two tops plus a third once the \DQ is out — nine is there if the diamond guess is right. You hold \DA\DJ\D7 opposite \DK\DT\D2, missing only the \DQ in a two-way finesse. Here the auction itself is a clue: East overcalled spades.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \S3, a singleton, supporting partner's spade overcall — so East is the one long in spades, as the bidding already suggested. East's spade length means East has fewer cards to spare in the other suits, but it also marks East as the hand with the high-card values to justify the overcall, with the defence's 16 points concentrated there. Counting vacant places: with East loaded in spades and strength, the missing \DQ rates to sit with East rather than the near-broke West. Draw trumps, then lead a low diamond from dummy toward your \DA\DJ and finesse the jack into East. The overcall makes this read a strong one, though still an inference.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] East's spade overcall and West's singleton-spade raise-by-lead told the whole story: the strength and the shape were with East, so the queen sat onside for the jack finesse. An opponent's bid is the most reliable two-way clue of all — use it. Nine tricks, well placed.}
