[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \S4, which looks like fourth-best from length, and as the spades develop East rates to show up with the long, strong spade holding. The hand long in spades has fewer cards left in the other suits — by vacant places, the shorter-spade defender (West) has more room for diamonds, but the queen tends to follow the high-card weight, and East holds the spade honors. Watch which defender turns up short in diamonds: when East is long in spades and packed with honors there, treat the diamond queen as likelier sitting with East and lead a low diamond from dummy toward your \DA\DJ, finessing the jack. As ever, weigh the evidence rather than bank on it.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] East's spade length and honors, against West's lead from length, pointed the diamond queen to the right for the jack finesse. Reading the side suits to place a missing honor is the core skill of the two-way guess — you found the clue and took the right finesse. Ten tricks home.}
