[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \HK, top of the \HA\HK, and rates to hold heart length to go with it. As you draw trumps and play clubs, count West's red cards: a defender long in hearts has fewer vacant places left for diamonds. When West turns up short in diamonds and East follows to the length, the missing \DQ rates to sit with West's partner — East — so lead toward your \DA\DJ and finesse the jack. But note the balance: West holds most of the defensive strength here, which can tug the queen the other way, so count the actual diamond lengths before you commit, and let the longer-diamond hand decide the direction. Whichever side the count favors, take that finesse; if it is genuinely even, lead toward the hand the lead and length point to and accept it as a near coin-flip.

